<HEADLINE>
<P>
FASHION: BEYOND BASIC BLACK; 
</P>
<P>
ACTOR RAY LIOTTA SHOWS THAT GOOD GUYS DON'T ALWAYS WEAR WHITE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Mary Rourke, Mary Rourke is a Times staff writer. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Black shirts, the kind that give a man an air of intrigue, are under 
reconstruction. Far from "basic," the new models have so many extras they make 
the others look as plain as starter homes. There's the playful black shirt with 
silver airplanes for buttons; the fancy-front model with black satin braid; the 
romantic rendition covered with red roses. This new development in menswear has 
a counterpart of sorts in home furniture. Consider an armchair made of 
corrugated cardboard. Designed by architect Frank Gehry, it has all the 
features of the greats from the past: round, rolling arms, an ample back and a 
deep, roomy feeling. But there's no mistaking Gehry's model for a chair from 
another era. The "Sherman," pictured here, is like this season's shirts. It 
moves a classic design into modern times. 
</P>
<P>
Grooming: Victor Vidal / Cloutier; stylist: Joanna Dendel 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, COLOR, Cotton shirt with silver airplane buttons by Le Garage, $135, 
also shown near left, is from Madeleine Gallay, West Hollywood. Pleated 
gabardine pants by Zanella are $225 at Sami Dinar, Beverly Hills. Black leather 
oxfords by Joan and David, $195, are at Fred Segal Feet, Melrose Avenue. Frank 
Gehry corrugated cardboard chair, $1,500, available by order from the Fred 
Hoffman Gallery, Santa Monica. ; Photo, COLOR, Rue des Artistes satin-braided 
dress shirt, $88, is at Traffic, Beverly Center. Joseph Jeans, $70, are from 
Fred Segal, Melrose Avenue. Black suede shoes with crepe soles by Joan and 
David, $195, are from Silver Feet, Brentwood. ; Photo, COLOR, Actor Ray Liotta 
starred in "Dominick and Eugene" and will next appear in "Shoeless Joe," a 
baseball story, due out this spring. John Colao 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
