<HEADLINE>
<P>
HOW COULD YOU . . . 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Thanks for finally including one of my productions in Pop Eye's Bottom 10 list 
("The Worst of 1988," by Patrick Goldstein, Jan. 8). 
</P>
<P>
After so many years of having one popular group after another receive a 
critical bashing from The Times, only to miss the Worst 10 list, I finally made 
it with Poison. Guess this goes to show that four Top 10 singles and 5 million 
copies sold won't hurt an album's chances of earning a spot on your list. 
</P>
<P>
Perhaps next year Poison will be lucky enough to come in higher than No. 9: A 
spot in the list's Worst-5 might mean sales of 10 million! 
</P>
<P>
TOM WERMAN 
</P>
<P>
Studio City 
</P>
<P>
 A case of different strokes for different folks. Goldstein's list was the 
result of a poll of 40 writers, deejays, record executives and others in the 
music industry. 
