<TEXT>
<P>
A state appellate court opinion has restricted a Kern County school district's 
ability to ban two books from its curriculum and said the school board had no 
authority to ban the books if the decision was based on religious grounds. The 
case stems from a 1986 lawsuit filed by English teacher Lee McCarthy against 
school administrators and Wasco Union High School District's Board of Trustees 
after the principal said "Grendel" by John Gardner and "One Hundred Years of 
Solitude" by Gabriel Garcia Marquez could no longer be used in school. A school 
administrator had expressed concerns about the books' vulgarity and profanity, 
and described "Grendel" as "anti-God, anti-religion and anti-personal dignity." 
The Court of Appeal reinstated the lawsuit, which had been dismissed in 1987 by 
a Kern County judge, and held that the school board had no authority to ban the 
books based on religious grounds. 
